Create a Culture of Accessibility

01

Creating a culture of accessibility goes beyond just our own efforts.

In the following lessons, you will learn how to get started with making a change across your team and your organization.

This is no easy task as individuals, yet it is essential to move accessibility efforts forward.

Creating a Culture of Accessibility

It's important to elevate accessibility awareness beyond only development teams.

The truth is that a whole organization needs to be on board, including design and creative, product managers, executives, and all the stakeholders in between.

We need leadership to be on board so we can get adequate time to address accessibility. This might might look like prioritizing efforts that increase the accessibility of the product vs. time to add new features.

Depending on your role, you might feel as if you're looking up at a mountain and thinking: "I'm supposed to manage up with all these people above me?"

The short answer to that question is yes.

The longer answer is that it's necessary to speak up about the importance of accessibility. But this can be difficult with power dynamics and organizational friction that make challenging the status quo hard.

Start by doing what you can. Make an impact in the areas you can influence. Talk to your manager and encourage them to communicate the importance of accessibility further up the chain.

Design Ableism Out of Systems

Ableism is social prejudice and discrimination against people with disabilities.

If we're not building things with accessibility in mind, we are perpetuating this system.

Without accessibility, we are impacting people and excluding them from using our products and services.

What Accessibility Looks Like Day-to-Day

Here's what it looks like when you consider accessibility throughout the software development lifecycle:

  • Asking questions about accessibility early in a project.
  • Advocating for input from people with disabilities.
  • Giving people credit for their feedback and ideas.
  • Pushing back when a design needs to be rethought.
  • Highlighting accessibility guidelines and best practices.
  • Making accessibility part of the “definition of done.”
  • Holding people accountable for ableism.

“Is Our Website WCAG Compliant?”

Sometimes people require hard numbers and facts to convince a manager or other high-level stakeholder, for example. This type of person usually needs a set of requirements spelled out, which is where WCAG comes in.

As you work to make an impact and gain buy-in, you might get asked this question from leadership:

“Is our website WCAG compliant?”

Being “compliant” (also called “conforming”) is a hard thing to answer! The people asking are typically looking for a quick yes/no response.

Not to make you feel overwhelmed, but there's always more you can do. “We aim to meet WCAG” with an open dialogue for user feedback, and a legitimate and timely process to handle issues is likely more realistic.

Accessibility is a moving target as screens on your site or app are updated, features are added, and general bug fixes are applied from the backlog. Browsers and screen readers also change from time to time in ways that impact access. So even if you could claim compliance at one moment in time, it probably wouldn't last for these reasons.

In general, I suggest highlighting existing accessibility issues to leadership that needs fixing as a first response.

Once you've identified the known issues and developed a plan for fixing them (while continuously testing for new issues), then you will be in a better position to answer the compliance question.

One thing that definitely won't support compliance is a bunch of accessibility issues that never get closed.

Qualities For Creating a Culture of Accessibility

It requires bravery to challenge the status quo. Pushing for accessibility within your team, organization, and the community at large is not easy.

These are a couple of the qualities that may help you when pushing for accessibility:

  • Curiosity to learn about disabled people's experiences.
  • Humility to recognize you don't know everything.
  • Patience when persuading colleagues to get on board.
  • Frankness to acknowledge what's really at stake for people with disabilities.
  • Bravery to challenge ableism and the status quo.
  • Kindness to yourself that organizational friction can be very difficult to navigate.
  • Acceptance that accessibility is often a thankless job.
